		<img width="2500" height="1200" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="little brown bat" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats-2048x983.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-alaska-brown-bats-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption"><em>Myotis lucifugus</em>, commonly referred to as the little brown bat, is one of the most widespread species of bats in North America, but its behavior in Alaska remains largely a mystery. Photo by Michael Code</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Bats of the Midnight Sun</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Active in daylight during the Arctic summer and hibernating during the long winter nights, Alaska’s little brown bats are a unique population. Can their niche lives help them avoid white-nose syndrome?</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						Text by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/trina-moyles/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Trina Moyles</a>								<br/>
							Photos by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/micheal-code/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Michael Code</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
